Harvard students take a course on enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year makes all its undergraduate students get more sleep in an attempt to counteract the growing macho culture of studying by opposing coffee-driven 'heeling sessions'.
An academic found that students at the world's top university are often ignorant when it comes to the basic principles of how to care for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes to be the first of his kind in the U.S.
He was inspired to start the course after he gave a talk about the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
'At the end of it one girl approached me and said, 'Why do they tell me this first, in my senior year?'
She said that no one had yet told her how important sleep was--which surprised me,' he said to The Telegraph.
The course, first offered that year, explains to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves their overall well - being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students had been seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
The hour course involves some interactive tasks.
In one department there is a picture of a dormitory, where students on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes and books should click to be told about the effect of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is influenced by lack of sleep and the importance of a sleep time routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term loss of risk from heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer can increase.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
'We know it won't change students' behavior immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know--just as you have the right to know the health effect of choosing to smoke cigarettes,' added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride to study 'hellday' still exists, he said, and added that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
To make sure that you get enough sleep of good quality, a student's 'secret weapon' should be to avoid stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said--even to avoid it from putting on weight, because sleep deprivation puts the brain in a starvation mode, which makes you feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studied chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design the course after he went to Harvard during his first year.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to work for a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the institution where people compete.
Prof. Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when they go to sleep, as well as when to wake up, and to be aware of the damaging effect of 'blue light' emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which may disturb your circadian rhythm and may cause you to struggle to touch the sheep.
